{"title_page": "Second Great Fire of London", "text_new": "{{short description|Air raid by Germany against London in 1940}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title = Second Great Fire of London\n| partof = [[the Blitz]]\n| image = View from St Paul's Cathedral after the Blitz.jpg\n| caption =  The view from the roof of [[St Paul's Cathedral]] towards the [[Old Bailey]] after the second Great Fire of London\n| location = London, England\n| target =City of London\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.51|N|0.09|W|region:UK_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| date = {{start and end dates|1940|12|29|1940|12|30|df=yes}}\n| time-begin = 6:15 pm\n| time-end = 4:00 am<ref name=\"BT\">{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Rhys |title=December 29, 1940: St Paul's stands defiant as second Great Fire of London rages |url=http://home.bt.com/news/on-this-day/december-29-1940-st-pauls-stands-defiant-as-second-great-fire-of-london-rages-11363951825843 |publisher=BT News |date=22 May 2017 |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n| timezone = UTC+00:00\n| type = [[Airstrike|Air raid]]\n| fatalities = 160\n| injuries = 250\n| perp = ''[[Luftwaffe]]''\n| assailants =\n| motive =\n}}\nThe '''Second Great Fire of London''' in December 1940 was one of the most destructive air raids of [[the Blitz]] during World War II. The [[Luftwaffe]] raid caused fires over an area greater than that of the [[Great Fire of London]] in 1666,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://londonist.com/2015/12/second-great-fire-of-london|title=Marking 75 Years Since The Second Great Fire Of London|date=2015-12-28|work=Londonist|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> leading one American correspondent to say in a cable to his office that \"The second Great Fire of London has begun\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-12016916|title=How did St Paul's survive the Blitz?|date=2010-12-29|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> Fires started by the raid included an incendiary bomb that broke through the dome of [[St Paul's Cathedral]], which was being guarded by a fire watch team at the behest of the Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]].\n\n==Attack==\nOn the night of 29\u201330 December 1940, approximately 100,000 bombs fell on the city.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Germans dispatched 136 [[bomber]]s to the city. Fewer incendiaries were dropped than in the raids of 15 November or 8 December. The raid was focused on a part of the city that contained many non-residential buildings, such as churches, offices, and warehouses. Many of these were locked and were not covered by the Fire Watchers Order of September 1940,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=A history of London|last=1947\u2013|first=Inwood, Stephen|date=1998|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=0-333-67153-8|location=London|oclc=40517708}}</ref> which applied to places of work with at least 30 employees, warehouses with an area of {{convert|50000|cuft|m3|-2|lk=on}} and [[sawmill]]s or timber yards with more than 50,000 cubic feet of [[Lumber|timber]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firefightersmemorial.org.uk/index.php/in-memoriam/fire-watchers-fire-guards|title=Fire Watchers/Fire Guards|last=User|first=Super|website=www.firefightersmemorial.org.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Incendiary device|Incendiary bombs]] were the main armament that night. Moderately small, at {{convert|12|x|3|in|cm|0}} \u2014 each bomber was equipped with approximately 180 of them \u2014 the bombs carried [[magnesium]] and started fires. The raid saw 1,500 fires begin in the city.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Firefighting==\n[[File:A House Collapsing on Two Firemen, Shoe Lane, London, EC4 (Art.IWM ART LD 1353).jpg|thumb|upright|''A House Collapsing on Two Firemen, Shoe Lane, London, EC4.'']]\nFirefighters' efforts were hampered by a water shortage. The main [[Water supply network|water-main]] in [[City of London|the City]] was bombed. Units trying to get water from other [[hydrant]]s caused the [[Pressure|water pressure]] to drop. Efforts to draw water from the [[River Thames]] were hampered by the [[Tide|low tide]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The fire brigade's difficulties were further exacerbated by wind, combined with the concentrated area of the attack.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTwelve of those killed in the raid were firefighters, while 250 were injured.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nArtist [[Leonard Rosoman]] was serving with the [[Auxiliary Fire Service]] on the night of the raid. While fighting a fire in Shoe Lane, Rosoman was relieved of his hose. Moments later a wall collapsed, burying the two firefighters working where Rosoman had just been. The moment haunted Rosoman for the rest of his life. He immortalised the scene in his painting ''A House Collapsing on Two Firemen, Shoe Lane, London, EC4.'' [[William Sansom]], a friend of Rosoman's who would go on to become a novelist and travel writer, survived the incident. The fireman who relieved Rosoman of his hose was killed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/art-obituaries/9129591/Leonard-Rosoman.html|title=Leonard Rosoman|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2012-03-07|access-date=2018-05-06|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nSam Chauveau of the [[London Fire Brigade]] described the scene that faced the fire fighters: <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=By the time we finished tackling the fires on the roof of the [Stock] Exchange, the sky, which was ebony black when we first got up there, was now changing to a yellowy orange colour. It looked like there was an enormous circle of fire, including St Paul's churchyard.|sign=|source=}}\n\n==St Paul's Cathedral==\n[[St Paul's Cathedral]] and the immediate area was struck by 28 incendiary bombs. Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] sent the message that \"St Paul's must be saved at all costs\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://artsandculture.google.com/exhibit/0wKSdsTj80dIJQ|title=St Paul's Watch \u2013 Google Arts & Culture|work=Google Cultural Institute|access-date=2018-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA famous [[photograph]], ''[[St Paul's Survives]]'', was taken from the roof of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' building (Northcliffe House on Carmelite Street) by Herbert Mason. Mason was the chief photographer at the ''Daily Mail'', and was on the roof firewatching when he took the picture. Mason described the moment he created the photograph \u2013 \n\n{{Quote|text=I focused at intervals as the great dome loomed up through the smoke... The glare of many fires and sweeping clouds of smoke kept hiding the shape. Then a wind sprang up. Suddenly, the shining cross, dome, and towers stood out like a symbol in the inferno. The scene was unbelievable. In that moment or two, I released my shutter.|sign=|source=<ref name=\"amateur\">{{cite web |title=St Paul's Survives by Herbert Mason \u2013 Iconic Photograph |url=https://www.amateurphotographer.co.uk/iconic-images/st-pauls-survives-by-herbert-mason-iconic-photograph-11041 |website=Amateur Photographer |date=27 November 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nThe camera is believed to have been a Van Neck on a quarter plate glass negative. The Royal Photographic Society, Magazine ''Photographic Journal,'' remarked on the brightness of the scene,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orca.cf.ac.uk/107159/1/Allbeson%20-%20Visualizing%20Wartime%20Destruction%20and%20Postwar%20Reconstruction.pdf|title=VisualizingWartime Destruction and Postwar Reconstruction:Herbert Mason's Photograph of St. Paul's Reevaluated|last=Allbeson|first=Tom|website=Online Research @ Cardiff}}</ref> saying that \"The light that was available for an instantaneous exposure is an indication of the fierceness and extent of the fire.\"\n\nVolunteers serving as part of the St Paul\u2019s Watch patrolled the iconic building.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Watch was first put together during the [[World War I|First World War]]. Then it was meant to protect the building from German [[Zeppelin]] raids. With the outbreak of the [[World War II|Second World War]], the group was reconstituted to guard against the anticipated air raids.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAmerican correspondent [[Ernie Pyle]] observed the raid from a balcony:\n\n{{Quote|text=Into the dark shadowed spaces below us, while we watched, whole batches of incendiary bombs fell. We saw two dozen go off in two seconds. They flashed terrifically, then quickly simmered down to pin points of dazzling white, burning ferociously\u2026 The greatest of all the fires was directly in front of us. Flames seemed to whip hundreds of feet into the air. Pinkish-white smoke ballooned upward in a great cloud, and out of this cloud there gradually took shape\u2014so faintly at first that we weren't sure we saw correctly\u2014the gigantic dome of St Paul's Cathedral. St Paul's was surrounded by fire, but it came through. It stood there in its enormous proportions\u2014growing slowly clearer and clearer, the way objects take shape at dawn. It was like a picture of some miraculous figure that appears before peace-hungry soldiers on a battlefield.|sign=|source=<ref name=\"amateur\"/>}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe publishing industry bore heavy losses in the raid. [[Ave Maria Lane]] and [[Paternoster Row]], an area known since the 19th century as the centre of the London [[publishing]] and book trade,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victorianlondon.org/districts/paternoster.htm |title=Districts \u2013 Streets \u2013 Paternoster Row |publisher=Victorian London |date= |accessdate=2016-11-19}}</ref><ref>James Raven. The business of books: booksellers and the English Book Trade. 2007</ref><ref>{{cite book | chapter = Paternoster Row | title = Old and New London: Volume 1 | year = 1878 | pages = 274\u2013281 | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.aspx?pubid=339 | chapterurl = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=45042 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A Pictorial and Descriptive Guide to London and Its Environs: With Two Large Section Plans of Central London...|publisher=Ward, Lock & Company, Limited|date= 1819}}</ref> were badly hit, and the buildings and stock of 20 publishing houses were totally or partially destroyed. [[Worshipful Company of Stationers and Newspaper Makers|Stationers' Hall]], neighbouring offices, the book wholesalers Simpkin Marshall, and several bookshops were lost. An estimated five million books were [[Book burning|lost]] in the fires caused by tens of thousands of incendiary bombs.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://iconicphotos.wordpress.com/2010/11/12/london-blitz-29th-december-1940/ |title=London Blitz \u2013 29th December 1940 &#124; Iconic Photos |website=Iconicphotos.wordpress.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n\nIn some opinions, the economic damage from such large devastation of a major city is thought to have accelerated the [[Decolonization|collapse of the British Empire]], and the decline of the [[United Kingdom]] as a [[superpower]] in the decades following the war.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Publishers Association, 1896\u20131946, with an epilogue|last=1900\u20131978.|first=Kingsford, R. J. L. (Reginald John Lethbridge)|date=2010|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-13084-4|location=Cambridge|oclc=463638144}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last=Demarne |first=Cyril |authorlink=Cyril Demarne |title=The London Blitz: A Fireman's Tale (After the Battle) |edition=2nd |date=4 May 1991 |isbn=978-0-900913-67-9}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gaskin |first=Margaret |title=Blitz: The Story of December 29, 1940 |date=4 December 2006 |publisher=Harcourt |isbn=978-0-15-101404-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/blitzstoryofdece00gask }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-london-fire-raids-29th-30th-december-1940-1940-online \"BFI Player \u2013 London Fire Raids 29th\u201330th December 1940\"]\n* [http://film.britishcouncil.org/st-pauls-cathedral British Council \u2013 St. Paul's Cathedral] *29 December section begins at 8.29\n* [https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/london-before-the-blitz-england-pic-circa-1930s-the-scene-news-photo/79043069 Getty Images \u2013 Photograph showing Paternoster Row before the war]\n* [http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=340297001&objectId=700038&partId=1 British Museum \u2013 Sketch of bomb damage in the Paternoster Row area]\n\n{{WWII city bombing}}\n\n[[Category:1940 fires]]\n[[Category:1940 in London]]\n[[Category:Battle of Britain]]\n[[Category:Battles and military actions in London]]\n[[Category:British Empire in World War II]]\n[[Category:December 1940 events]]\n[[Category:Firebombings|London]]\n[[Category:Fires in London]]\n[[Category:History of the City of London]]\n[[Category:The Blitz]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom home front during World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Air raid by Germany against London in 1940}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title = Second Great Fire of London\n| partof = [[the Blitz]]\n| image = View from St Paul's Cathedral after the Blitz.jpg\n| caption =  The view from the roof of [[St Paul's Cathedral]] towards the [[Old Bailey]] after the second Great Fire of London\n| location = London, England\n| target =City of London\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.51|N|0.09|W|region:UK_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| date = {{start and end dates|1940|12|29|1940|12|30|df=yes}}\n| time-begin = 6:15 pm\n| time-end = 4:00 am<ref name=\"BT\">{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Rhys |title=December 29, 1940: St Paul's stands defiant as second Great Fire of London rages |url=http://home.bt.com/news/on-this-day/december-29-1940-st-pauls-stands-defiant-as-second-great-fire-of-london-rages-11363951825843 |publisher=BT News |date=22 May 2017 |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n| timezone = UTC+00:00\n| type = [[Airstrike|Air raid]]\n| fatalities = 160\n| injuries = 250\n| perp = ''[[Luftwaffe]]''\n| assailants =\n| motive =\n}}\nThe '''Second Great Fire of London''' in December 1940 was one of the most destructive air raids of [[the Blitz]] during World War II. The [[Luftwaffe]] raid caused fires over an area greater than that of the [[Great Fire of London]] in 1666,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://londonist.com/2015/12/second-great-fire-of-london|title=Marking 75 Years Since The Second Great Fire Of London|date=2015-12-28|work=Londonist|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> leading one American correspondent to say in a cable to his office that \"The second Great Fire of London has begun\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-12016916|title=How did St Paul's survive the Blitz?|date=2010-12-29|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> Fires started by the raid included an incendiary bomb that broke through the dome of [[St Paul's Cathedral]], which was being guarded by a fire watch team at the behest of the Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]].\n\n==Attack==\nOn the night of 29\u201330 December 1940, approximately 100,000 bombs fell on the city.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Germans dispatched 136 [[bomber]]s to the city. Fewer incendiaries were dropped than in the raids of 15 November or 8 December. The raid was focused on a part of the city that contained many non-residential buildings, such as churches, offices, and warehouses. Many of these were locked and were not covered by the Fire Watchers Order of September 1940,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=A history of London|last=1947\u2013|first=Inwood, Stephen|date=1998|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=0-333-67153-8|location=London|oclc=40517708}}</ref> which applied to places of work with at least 30 employees, warehouses with an area of {{convert|50000|cuft|m3|-2|lk=on}} and [[sawmill]]s or timber yards with more than 50,000 cubic feet of [[Lumber|timber]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firefightersmemorial.org.uk/index.php/in-memoriam/fire-watchers-fire-guards|title=Fire Watchers/Fire Guards|last=User|first=Super|website=www.firefightersmemorial.org.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Incendiary device|Incendiary bombs]] were the main armament that night. Moderately small, at {{convert|12|x|3|in|cm|0}} \u2014 each bomber was equipped with approximately 180 of them \u2014 the bombs carried [[magnesium]] and started fires. The raid saw 1,500 fires begin in the city.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Firefighting==\n[[File:A House Collapsing on Two Firemen, Shoe Lane, London, EC4 (Art.IWM ART LD 1353).jpg|thumb|upright|''A House Collapsing on Two Firemen, Shoe Lane, London, EC4.'']]\nFirefighters' efforts were hampered by a water shortage. The main [[Water supply network|water-main]] in [[City of London|the City]] was bombed. Units trying to get water from other [[hydrant]]s caused the [[Pressure|water pressure]] to drop. Efforts to draw water from the [[River Thames]] were hampered by the [[Tide|low tide]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The fire brigade's difficulties were further exacerbated by wind, combined with the concentrated area of the attack.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTwelve of those killed in the raid were firefighters, while 250 were injured.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nArtist [[Leonard Rosoman]] was serving with the [[Auxiliary Fire Service]] on the night of the raid. While fighting a fire in Shoe Lane, Rosoman was relieved of his hose. Moments later a wall collapsed, burying the two firefighters working where Rosoman had just been. The moment haunted Rosoman for the rest of his life. He immortalised the scene in his painting ''A House Collapsing on Two Firemen, Shoe Lane, London, EC4.'' [[William Sansom]], a friend of Rosoman's who would go on to become a novelist and travel writer, survived the incident. The fireman who relieved Rosoman of his hose was killed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/art-obituaries/9129591/Leonard-Rosoman.html|title=Leonard Rosoman|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2012-03-07|access-date=2018-05-06|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nSam Chauveau of the [[London Fire Brigade]] described the scene that faced the fire fighters: <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=By the time we finished tackling the fires on the roof of the [Stock] Exchange, the sky, which was ebony black when we first got up there, was now changing to a yellowy orange colour. It looked like there was an enormous circle of fire, including St Paul's churchyard.|sign=|source=}}\n\n==St Paul's Cathedral==\n[[St Paul's Cathedral]] and the immediate area was struck by 28 incendiary bombs. Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] sent the message that \"St Paul's must be saved at all costs\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://artsandculture.google.com/exhibit/0wKSdsTj80dIJQ|title=St Paul's Watch \u2013 Google Arts & Culture|work=Google Cultural Institute|access-date=2018-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA famous [[photograph]], ''[[St Paul's Survives]]'', was taken from the roof of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' building (Northcliffe House on Carmelite Street) by Herbert Mason. Mason was the chief photographer at the ''Daily Mail'', and was on the roof firewatching when he took the picture. Mason described the moment he created the photograph \u2013 \n\n{{Quote|text=I focused at intervals as the great dome loomed up through the smoke... The glare of many fires and sweeping clouds of smoke kept hiding the shape. Then a wind sprang up. Suddenly, the shining cross, dome, and towers stood out like a symbol in the inferno. The scene was unbelievable. In that moment or two, I released my shutter.|sign=|source=<ref name=\"amateur\">{{cite web |title=St Paul's Survives by Herbert Mason \u2013 Iconic Photograph |url=https://www.amateurphotographer.co.uk/iconic-images/st-pauls-survives-by-herbert-mason-iconic-photograph-11041 |website=Amateur Photographer |date=27 November 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nThe camera is believed to have been a Van Neck on a quarter plate glass negative. The Royal Photographic Society, Magazine ''Photographic Journal,'' remarked on the brightness of the scene,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orca.cf.ac.uk/107159/1/Allbeson%20-%20Visualizing%20Wartime%20Destruction%20and%20Postwar%20Reconstruction.pdf|title=VisualizingWartime Destruction and Postwar Reconstruction:Herbert Mason's Photograph of St. Paul's Reevaluated|last=Allbeson|first=Tom|website=Online Research @ Cardiff}}</ref> saying that \"The light that was available for an instantaneous exposure is an indication of the fierceness and extent of the fire.\"\n\nVolunteers serving as part of the St Paul\u2019s Watch patrolled the iconic building.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Watch was first put together during the [[World War I|First World War]]. Then it was meant to protect the building from German [[Zeppelin]] raids. With the outbreak of the [[World War II|Second World War]], the group was reconstituted to guard against the anticipated air raids.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAmerican correspondent [[Ernie Pyle]] observed the raid from a balcony:\n\n{{Quote|text=Into the dark shadowed spaces below us, while we watched, whole batches of incendiary bombs fell. We saw two dozen go off in two seconds. They flashed terrifically, then quickly simmered down to pin points of dazzling white, burning ferociously\u2026 The greatest of all the fires was directly in front of us. Flames seemed to whip hundreds of feet into the air. Pinkish-white smoke ballooned upward in a great cloud, and out of this cloud there gradually took shape\u2014so faintly at first that we weren't sure we saw correctly\u2014the gigantic dome of St Paul's Cathedral. St Paul's was surrounded by fire, but it came through. It stood there in its enormous proportions\u2014growing slowly clearer and clearer, the way objects take shape at dawn. It was like a picture of some miraculous figure that appears before peace-hungry soldiers on a battlefield.|sign=|source=<ref name=\"amateur\"/>}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe publishing industry bore heavy losses in the raid. [[Ave Maria Lane]] and [[Paternoster Row]], an area known since the 19th century as the centre of the London [[publishing]] and book trade,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victorianlondon.org/districts/paternoster.htm |title=Districts \u2013 Streets \u2013 Paternoster Row |publisher=Victorian London |date= |accessdate=2016-11-19}}</ref><ref>James Raven. The business of books: booksellers and the English Book Trade. 2007</ref><ref>{{cite book | chapter = Paternoster Row | title = Old and New London: Volume 1 | year = 1878 | pages = 274\u2013281 | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.aspx?pubid=339 | chapterurl = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=45042 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A Pictorial and Descriptive Guide to London and Its Environs: With Two Large Section Plans of Central London...|publisher=Ward, Lock & Company, Limited|date= 1819}}</ref> were badly hit, and the buildings and stock of 20 publishing houses were totally or partially destroyed. [[Worshipful Company of Stationers and Newspaper Makers|Stationers' Hall]], neighbouring offices, the book wholesalers Simpkin Marshall, and several bookshops were lost. An estimated five million books were [[Book burning|lost]] in the fires caused by tens of thousands of incendiary bombs.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://iconicphotos.wordpress.com/2010/11/12/london-blitz-29th-december-1940/ |title=London Blitz \u2014 29th December 1940 &#124; Iconic Photos |website=Iconicphotos.wordpress.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n\nIn some opinions, the economic damage from such large devastation of a major city is thought to have accelerated the [[Decolonization|collapse of the British Empire]], and the decline of the [[United Kingdom]] as a [[superpower]] in the decades following the war.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Publishers Association, 1896\u20131946, with an epilogue|last=1900\u20131978.|first=Kingsford, R. J. L. (Reginald John Lethbridge)|date=2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-13084-4|location=Cambridge|oclc=463638144}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last=Demarne |first=Cyril |authorlink=Cyril Demarne |title=The London Blitz: A Fireman's Tale (After the Battle) |edition=2nd |date=4 May 1991 |isbn=978-0-900913-67-9}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gaskin |first=Margaret |title=Blitz: The Story of December 29, 1940 |date=4 December 2006 |publisher=Harcourt |isbn=978-0-15-101404-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/blitzstoryofdece00gask }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-london-fire-raids-29th-30th-december-1940-1940-online \"BFI Player \u2013 London Fire Raids 29th\u201330th December 1940\"]\n* [http://film.britishcouncil.org/st-pauls-cathedral British Council \u2013 St. Paul's Cathedral] *29 December section begins at 8.29\n* [https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/london-before-the-blitz-england-pic-circa-1930s-the-scene-news-photo/79043069 Getty Images \u2013 Photograph showing Paternoster Row before the war]\n* [http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=340297001&objectId=700038&partId=1 British Museum \u2013 Sketch of bomb damage in the Paternoster Row area]\n\n{{WWII city bombing}}\n\n[[Category:1940 fires]]\n[[Category:1940 in London]]\n[[Category:Battle of Britain]]\n[[Category:Battles and military actions in London]]\n[[Category:British Empire in World War II]]\n[[Category:December 1940 events]]\n[[Category:Firebombings|London]]\n[[Category:Fires in London]]\n[[Category:History of the City of London]]\n[[Category:The Blitz]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom home front during World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe"